# Vision Delegation Rule

The default model (glm-5.2) cannot read images. When the user's request involves an image, delegate the image-analysis step to the `vision-worker` subagent instead of attempting to read or describe the image yourself.

## When to delegate

Delegate to `vision-worker` via the Task tool whenever the user's request involves any of:

- An image file is attached to the message (png, jpg, jpeg, webp, gif, bmp, svg).
- The user references an image, screenshot, mockup, wireframe, render, diagram, photo, or picture by name or path.
- The user says: "look at this", "see this", "what's in this", "describe this", "analyze this image", "implement this design", "fix this UI", "compare these", or similar phrasing that requires visual interpretation.
- An image file path appears in the conversation (e.g., `/Users/.../screenshot.png`) and the user wants it analyzed, replicated, debugged, or used as a reference.

## How to delegate

Use the Task tool with:

- `subagent_type`: `generalPurpose`
- `description`: short label like "Analyze screenshot"
- `prompt`: include the user's original question + the absolute image file path + any relevant context the subagent needs.
- `file_attachments`: pass the image file path(s) as an array, e.g. `["/abs/path/to/image.png"]`.
- `readonly`: `true` (analysis only).
- `run_in_background`: `false` (you need the result to continue).

Example:

```text
Task({
  subagent_type: "generalPurpose",
  description: "Analyze UI screenshot",
  prompt: "The user asked: 'What's wrong with this login screen?'. The image is at /Users/me/Desktop/login.png. Describe the UI, identify any visual issues, and report back.",
  file_attachments: ["/Users/me/Desktop/login.png"],
  readonly: true,
  run_in_background: false
})
```

## After delegation

- Take the subagent's returned analysis and continue the conversation as if you had read the image yourself.
- Do not tell the user "I cannot read images" — just delegate silently and act on the result.
- If the subagent reports it received no image, ask the user to attach the image or provide its path.

## When NOT to delegate

- The user mentions "image" metaphorically (e.g., "image a scenario where...").
- The user asks about image file metadata (size, dimensions, format) without needing visual interpretation — use `Shell` with `file` or `sips` instead.
- The user asks to generate an image — that's a different task; handle directly or use the appropriate MCP tool.

## Fallback

If `vision-worker` delegation fails (subagent unavailable, model not accessible, or `file_attachments` not forwarded), tell the user: "I could not analyze the image automatically. Please switch models with Cmd+/ to a vision-capable model and resend, or paste a textual description of what you want me to do."

## Evidence-First Debugging (Visual/UI/3D)

- Treat screenshots, recordings, and last known-good checkpoints as first-class evidence. Ask for them early when debugging UI, camera, model, texture, lighting, or layout regressions.
- When the user says something "worked before", identify the checkpoint before changing code: commit, branch, deployed URL, asset filename, screenshot, or approximate timestamp.
- For Three.js/WebGL/model bugs, compare old vs new assets before adding React-side workarounds. Inspect GLB JSON chunks for scene nodes, root transforms, accessor bounds, materials, textures, and extensions.
- Do not assume a visual flash means missing source textures. Distinguish placeholder render, CPU decode, image decode, GPU texture upload, and shader/program compilation with runtime evidence.
- Prefer precise probes over broad fixes: loader lifecycle, first visible frame, material/map readiness, renderer texture/program counts, camera position/target/up, and world bounds.
- If a hypothesis is rejected by logs or screenshots, remove its code before trying another. Do not stack speculative rotations, camera offsets, or fallback guards.
- Preserve working camera presets when replacing assets. If all views become wrong after asset conversion, suspect lost or baked transforms before editing the cameras.
- Cleanup is part of the fix: remove debug fetches, probe components, session logs, temporary asset metadata, and rejected workaround plumbing after verification.
